Standard uninstall (stop containers and remove the .ctem folder):

powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -Command "iwr https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tal-hash1/ctem/main/uninstall.ps1 -UseBasicParsing | iex"


Full cleanup (no prompts; also remove pulled images and volumes):

powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -Command "iwr https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tal-hash1/ctem/main/uninstall.ps1 -UseBasicParsing | iex; `
  .\uninstall.ps1 -Force -PurgeImages -PurgeVolumes"

If you already cloned/downloaded the repo

Run from the folder containing uninstall.ps1:

# standard uninstall (asks for confirmation)
.\uninstall.ps1

# no prompt
.\uninstall.ps1 -Force

# also remove images
.\uninstall.ps1 -PurgeImages

# also remove volumes
.\uninstall.ps1 -PurgeVolumes

# everything with no prompts
.\uninstall.ps1 -Force -PurgeImages -PurgeVolumes


What it does:

Stops the compose stack started by install.ps1

Removes the .ctem working directory

(Optional) Removes Docker images and volumes if you pass those flags

macOS / Linux (bash) â€” if you need it too

If you used the bash installer, the matching uninstaller (from earlier) is:

One-liner

/bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tal-hash1/ctem/main/uninstall.sh)"


From disk

# standard
./uninstall.sh
# no prompt
./uninstall.sh -f
# also remove images/volumes
./uninstall.sh -f --purge-images --purge-volumes
